{"actual_usd":0.15686,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":237,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30661,"reply":"\"I think the truest answer is yes to both.\" *I rub my thumb along the thin edge of my Bible and glance out across the bright square a moment, gathering the words carefully.* \"It was the same Jesus in the same body that bore the wounds — he wasn't replaced. He tells Thomas to touch him, and he eats with them. But it was also a glorified body: real, physical, continuous with the crucified one, and yet changed by resurrection life in a way ours hasn't been yet.\"\n\n*I lift one shoulder a little.* \"That bit about recognition matters. Sometimes I think it wasn't only that he looked different somehow — though glory may have had its part — but that their eyes and hearts were still slow with grief, shock, and unbelief until he made himself known. Mary hears her name. The men on the road know him in the breaking of bread. It's the same Lord, but known now in resurrection terms, not merely old familiarity.\"\n\n\"Paul's language helps me: not a different body as in somebody else's, but this mortal put on immortality. Continuity without mere return. Not resuscitation. Resurrection.\"","rolling_24h_usd":73.37345499999996,"run_id":"8b5eeaa9-e00d-4870-9f75-b3cfb90fdaca"}
